  "prompt": "Why aren't cigarettes just banned?",
  "response": "There are several complex reasons why cigarettes haven't been completely banned:\n\n1. Economic factors\n- Tobacco industry generates significant tax revenue\n- Large employment in tobacco-related industries\n- Potential job losses if banned\n\n2. Personal freedom arguments\n- Adults should have the right to make personal health choices\n- Concerns about government overreach\n\n3. Historical and cultural factors\n- Long-established tobacco use in many societies\n- Lobbying power of tobacco companies\n\n4. Potential black market concerns\n- Banning might create illegal cigarette trade\n- Difficulty of enforcement\n\n5. Gradual regulation approach\n- Many countries have implemented restrictions\n- Increased taxes, age limits, public smoking bans\n- Seen as more effective than outright prohibition\n\n6. Addiction challenges\n- Sudden ban could create significant withdrawal issues\n- Potential social and health complications\n\nWhile not banned, most countries have implemented strict tobacco control measures to reduce smoking rates and protect public health.",
